arch:property.oc:show_val: This unit is described as a bone cluster - ‘concentrated grouping of animal bones’ - within (17068), which is a ‘surface or dumped deposit’ in space 329, an open area. The space sheet indicates that (17068) was one of a series of levelling deposits in this space, each of which may have been used as a surface following deposition, as indicated by fire spots and occasional ash dumps. Since (17070) is a cluster there is no flot, but the entire 45 litre unit was dry-sieved. The assemblage is large for a cluster, with over 500 fragments, and could probably be better termed a concentration. The vast majority of the material is sheep-sized, with cattle-sized animals contributing less than 10% of fragments. Interestingly, almost all of the latter are scrap fragments, with cattle-sized specimens making up 10-15% of vertebrae, ribs, and long bone splinters but less than 5% of diagnostics. Less than 5% of specimens are hare-sized, and all of these are long bone or rib splinters. Anatomical representation is fairly balanced, with all major body parts and scrap categories present. Tarsals, phalanges, and especially carpals are underrepresented, although metapodials are not. The shortage of specimens from the feet would point towards post-consumption waste, although cranial pieces are reasonably well represented (albeit more fragmented than other body parts). These are dominated by alveolars and caprine teeth (upper and lower) but also include various sheep-sized skull portions and two female sheep frontals, one [F143] with a short horn and the other [F142] virtually hornless. Sheep-sized long bone cylinders and shaft fragments are common and fairly evenly distributed, but there is a surprising shortage of articular ends, despite little sign of gnawing (see below). This may reflect the retention of these parts for grease extraction following meat consumption, which is interesting given that the shafts appear less heavily processed than is often the case. Several cases of cut-marking on rib midshafts also point to post-consumption waste, although likely filleting marks are also present on some ribs. The material is in good condition, with a median fragment size of perhaps 40mm. The modal size category is probably 45-55mm, but larger specimens are also common, with around 5% of pieces over 80mm. Spiral breaks are fairly common, indicating that post-depositional breakage was relatively limited. The scrap:diagnostic ratio is unremarkable at a little over 1:1. Surface condition is good, with around 90% of fragments at stage 3 (slight weathering) and the remainder divided between stages 2 (very slight) and 4 (moderate). Gnawing is rare, and usually minor where present, but it is notable that the clearest five cases are observed on cattle-sized specimens. There is very little apparent digestion. Colouration is moderately consistent, with few specimens conspicuously different from the rest, but is not nearly as uniform as might be expected from a genuinely primary deposit. Around 5% of the sheep-sized long bone splinters stand out as unusually ‘fresh’, with a pale yellow colour and very slight weathering. Burning is fairly rare: a little fewer than 5% of fragments are carbonized and a few specimens (~1%) are partly calcined. The unit has low to moderate integrity, resembling a well-preserved midden deposit in some ways but having greater homogeneity. While the anatomical representation is fairly balanced amongst sheep-sized specimens, and a relatively small number of individuals could be represented, there is no particular reason to believe that this is the case, especially given a moderate degree of variation in colouration and overall appearance. An absence of articulations should not be taken too seriously, however, given the aforementioned shortage of articular ends. At the same time, a couple of unfused vertebral/sacral epiphyses were clearly articulated in the ground, indicating a lack of post-depositional disturbance. This impression is supported both by the good condition of the material and by its consistency -most specimens seem to have had similar, although certainly not identical, taphonomic histories, with little sign of extensive reworking. The material is all fairly lightly processed and, while almost certainly not from a single event, does at least seem to be from the same type of event. The small group of cattle-sized specimens - particularly four or five with unusually clear gnawing - seems likely to have derived from a different source to the rest of the material. Overall, the assemblage is certainly not primary, but should probably be considered secondary rather than tertiary, with final deposition taking place shortly after consumption in most cases. Its inclusion as a concentration within what appears to be a levelling deposit seems likely to represent a discrete dumping event involving fairly fresh material from various primary contexts, along with some reworked pieces that may have been present in the surrounding matrix of unit (17068).

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
